<sect3 status="final" id="low_light">

  <title>Low light</title>

  <indexterm>
    <primary>modules</primary>
    <secondary>lowlight</secondary>
  </indexterm>

  <indexterm>
    <primary>lowlight</primary>
  </indexterm>

  <sect4>

    <title>Overview</title>

    <informaltable frame="none">
      <tgroup cols="2" colsep="0" rowsep="0">
        <colspec colwidth="6*"/>
        <colspec colwidth="4*"/>
        <tbody>
          <row>
            <entry>
              <para>
                The <emphasis>low light</emphasis> module allows one to simulate human lowlight
                vision, thus providing ability to make lowlight pictures look closer to reality.
                It can also be used to perform a day to night conversion.
              </para>

              <para>
                The idea is to calculate a
                <ulink url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scotopic_vision">scotopic
                vision</ulink> image which is perceived by rods rather than than cones in the
                eye under low light. Scotopic lightness then is mixed with photopic value
                (regular color image pixel) using some blending function. Also this module is
                able to simulate the
                <ulink url="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purkinje_effect">Purkinje
                effect</ulink> by adding some blueness to the dark parts of the image.
              </para>
            </entry>
            <entry>
              <graphic fileref="darkroom/modules/images/lowlight.png" scalefit="1" width="80%" align="center" />
            </entry>
          </row>
        </tbody>
      </tgroup>
    </informaltable>

  </sect4>

  <sect4>

    <title>Usage</title>

    <para>
      This module comes with several presets. Give them a try to get a better feeling how it
      works.
    </para>

    <sect5>
      <title>curve</title>
      <para>
        The horizontal axis is about pixel lightness from dark (left) to bright (right). The
        vertical axis represents the kind of vision from night vision (bottom) to day vision
        (top)
      </para>
    </sect5>

    <sect5>
      <title>blue</title>
      <para>
        Set the blue hint in shadows (Purkinje effect).
      </para>
    </sect5>

  </sect4>

